    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An escrow account is essentially a neutral, third-party vault where funds and documents are held by a trusted agent until all conditions of the sale are fully met. In Toronto, this is crucial because it protects both you and the seller from financial risk, ensuring that the buyer's money isn't released until the property is legally transferred and the seller's funds are secured. It's like a secure, locked box that only opens when every single requirement of the contract is satisfied, preventing any last-minute surprises or fraud.\n\nWithout escrow, there would be no guarantee that the seller receives their full price before handing over the keys, nor would the buyer be assured they get a clear title to the property. It acts as the ultimate safety net, coordinating the complex web of inspections, appraisals, and legal paperwork so that nothing goes wrong. If you're worried about the process, remember that a good realtor will guide you through the escrow instructions, ensuring you understand every step before you sign anything.\n\nThink of it as a game of musical chairs where the music only stops when everyone is seated in the right spot. If the music stops early, the game is over, and no one wins. If the music stops late, the game is",
