    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that musical chairs thing makes sense i guess lol. but who actually holds the money? like is it the bank or a lawyer or something? and is it a huge risk if that person messes up or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The money is typically held by a title company, a specialized mortgage lender, or sometimes a lawyer's trust account, depending on your province and the specific agreement. In Toronto, it's often a title company because they are experts in the land registry system, which is a bit more complex than just holding cash. They are not just a random person; they are a licensed professional bound by strict laws to keep those funds separate from their own personal accounts.\n\nIf that person were to mess up, the risk is actually quite low because of these strict regulations and insurance policies. If a title company fails or mismanages the funds, there are usually compensation schemes or insurance in place to protect the buyer and seller. It's a highly regulated environment where the \"house\" of the financial transaction is built on very sturdy foundations, not just trust.\n\nThink of it like a very high-security bank vault managed by a team of experts who have to pass rigorous background checks. Even if one person in the team is a bit clumsy, the system has multiple locks and alarms to ensure the money stays safe until the very last moment. The whole point is that the money doesn't move until the deed is officially transferred, which is the final \"key\" that unlocks",
