      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to feel cautious, and honestly, that instinct is your first line of defense against any potential \"shady\" behavior, even though the system is heavily regulated. While the escrow officer is bound by law, the real \"traps\" during closing in Toronto aren't usually about theft from the pot, but rather about administrative errors, missing documents, or last-minute changes to the contract that could delay the transfer.\n\nTo protect yourself, you should definitely review the \"Closing Disclosure\" and \"Statement of Adjustments\" thoroughly before signing the final paperwork. This is where you'll see exactly how much money is going to each party, including prorated taxes, utilities, and any adjustments for rent or special assessments. If you spot a discrepancy here, it's better to ask the realtor or your lawyer to clarify it immediately rather than hoping the numbers balance out later.\n\nThink of the closing phase as a final \"gathering of the troops\" before the big battle begins. Just as a squad leader would double-check the equipment list before the mission, you need to ensure every document is signed and every wire transfer is confirmed. If anything feels off, don't just sign blindly; pause and ask for a second opinion from your",
